ads/2021/08/23110018/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-3-122x300.jpg 122w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110018/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-3-49x120.jpg 49w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110018/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-3-768x1888.jpg 768w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110018/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-3-625x1536.jpg 625w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110018/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-3-833x2048.jpg 833w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110018/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-3-696x1711.jpg 696w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110018/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-3-1068x2626.jpg 1068w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110018/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-3-171x420.jpg 171w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110018/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-3-scaled.jpg 1041w\"></a></p><p>The steel forks will be offered with a standard 1 1/8″ steerer, and will be available in both a Gravel/Road model and an MTB fork. The Gravel/Road fork will use a 401mm axle tor crown measurement, a 47mm offset, 100x12mm axle, and will have 700c x 50mm tire clearance.</p><p>The Mountain Type II-R fork will clear up to 27.5 x 3″ or 29 x 2.25″ on the same fork, with an axle to crown of 419mm, a 47mm offset, and a 100x12mm thru axle. Both forks will sell for $500 each.</p><p><a href=\"https://s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2.jpg\"><img loading=\"lazy\" src=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2.jpg\" alt=\"Steve Potts x Suzue hubs\" width=\"1200\" height=\"900\" data-ezsrcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2.jpg 1200w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-297x223.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-800x600.jpg 800w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-120x90.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-768x576.jpg 768w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-696x522.jpg 696w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-1068x801.jpg 1068w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-560x420.jpg 560w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-80x60.jpg 80w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-265x198.jpg 265w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px\" ezimgfmt=\"rs rscb28 src ng ngcb28 srcset\" data-ezsrc=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2.jpg\" srcset=\"https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2.jpg 1200w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-297x223.jpg 297w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-800x600.jpg 800w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-120x90.jpg 120w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-768x576.jpg 768w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-696x522.jpg 696w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-1068x801.jpg 1068w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-560x420.jpg 560w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-80x60.jpg 80w,https://bikerumor.com/ezoimgfmt/s3.amazonaws.com/www.bikerumor.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/08/23110000/Steve-Potts-Component-line-tange-seiki-suzue-2-265x198.jpg 265w\"></a></p><p>At the hub, Potts is partnering with Suzue on these classy spinners, which are available in a few different configurations. The Front hubs will fit standard 100x9mm QR, 100×15 and 100x12mm thru axles while the rear will fit 142×12 TA and 135×9 QR spacing. Offered in six bolt only, Potts tells us they will be offered in 32h for now, with more options on the way. Rear hubs will be offered with Campy, XDR, and Shimano freehub bodies, and in black or silver hub shells.</p><h2>What Else?</h2><p>For now, Steve only sent over the fork and the hub photos, but we’re told that more components are in the works for 2021 and 2022.“Handlebars by Nitto are already in production. I am also looking into saddles, tires and wheelsets moving forward, but it has been slow going, since the factories that I want to work with are so overbooked.” Steve goes on to say that this will include new tire designs made by Panaracer. “I am excited to offer this new line of high quality products and to be working with the very best in the industry. Forks and Hubs are already available from Merry Sales , BTI, and <a href=\"https://www.stevepottsbicycles.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Steve Potts Bicycles.</a></p><div id=\":10r\"><h3>Pricing &amp; Options</h3><div><ul><li>Steve <span>Potts</span> Fork Type II-R Gravel Fork 650b/700c MSRP&nbsp; $500.00</li><li>Steve <span>Potts</span> Fork Type II-R MTB Silver/Black&nbsp; MSRP&nbsp; $500.00</li><li>Steve <span>Potts</span> / Suzue Alpina Campy Cassette Body&nbsp; MSRP &nbsp; $140.00</li><li>Steve <span>Potts</span> / Suzue&nbsp; Alpina XDR Cassette Body&nbsp; MSRP&nbsp; $140.00</li><li>Steve <span>Potts</span> /&nbsp; Alpina Front M12 End Caps (Black)&nbsp; MSRP &nbsp; $30.00</li><li>Steve <span>Potts</span> /&nbsp; Alpina Front M12 End Caps (Silver)&nbsp; MSRP&nbsp; $30.00</li><li>Steve <span>Potts</span> / Suzue Alpina Front 9mm QR End Caps (Black)&nbsp; MSRP $30.00</li><li>Steve <span>Potts</span> / Suzue Alpina Front 9mm QR End Caps (Silver)&nbsp; MSRP $30.00</li><li>Suzue Steve <span>Potts</span> /&nbsp; Rear 10mm QR 135 O.L.D. End Caps( silver or black )&nbsp; MSRP $30.00</li><li>Steve <span>Potts</span> /&nbsp; Alpina Shimano Cassette Body&nbsp; MSRP $140.00</li><li>Steve <span>Potts</span> / Suzue Alpina Front Disc Hub (Black, 32 hole)&nbsp; MSRP&nbsp; $180.00</li><li>Steve <span>Potts</span> / Suzue Alpina Front Disc Hub (Silver, 32 hole)&nbsp; MSRP&nbsp; $180.00</li><li>Steve <span>Potts</span> / Suzue Alpina Rear Disc Hub (Black, 32 hole)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; MSRP&nbsp; $300.00</li><li>Steve <span>Potts</span> / Suzue Alpina Rear Disc Hub (Silver, 32 hole)&nbsp; MSRP&nbsp; $300.00</li></ul></div></div></div></div>","author":"Zach Overholt","siteTitle":"Bikerumor","siteHash":"49f427af0a926f4232eb837006841d7242e153e3afbb590f32e4b104ea3e2718","entryHash":"9e4d02b4c51b3f704393fb018aa41f22bb0f07f317ba18180fb137cf0437d198","category":"Cycling"}